The task:¶

This notebook is a comprehensive guide for text classification tasks using popular machine learning techniques. It provides a deep dive into the implementation and analysis of Naive Bayes, Support Vector Machines (SVM), and Random Forests, and also covering aspects such as evaluation, interpretation, and comparison of these models.

We will work through a sentiment classification problem, using a movie reviews data set where we know the "negative" and "positive" labels for each of the movie reviews. We'll set some of these reviews aside for a test set and train our models on the remainder as a training set, using unigram presence as the features. Then we'll evaluate the predictions quantitatively as well as look at some ways to interpret what the models tell us.

We are using Pang and Lee dataset of 2000 movie reviews and the scikit-learn library.

This tutorial provides details on the models and is aimed at Python users. I walk throught all the steps of converting text into a vectorized format that can be input into classification models, I provide a summary of how the models work, walk throught the steps to extract feature importance from these models and vizualize them.

Create the doument term matrix¶

You can create different types of features for text classification using scikit-learn.

  • To create word presence features, use CountVectorizer with binary=True.
  • For word count features, simply use CountVectorizer with default settings.
  • To generate TF-IDF features, use TfidfVectorizer, which automatically computes both term frequency (TF) and inverse document frequency (IDF) scores for each word.
  • By adjusting the parameters of these vectorizers, such as binary, max_df, min_df, and ngram_range, you can customize the feature extraction process according to your specific requirements.

In our example, we will only use the word presence features (Binary Vectorizer).

Naive Bayes¶

Naive Bayes is a probabilistic classifier based on Bayes' theorem, which calculates the probability of a given class (e.g., positive or negative sentiment) given the input features (e.g., words in a document).

Independence Assumption: Naive Bayes operates under the assumption that the features (words) are conditionally independent given the class label. This is known as the "naive" assumption. In our example, Naive Bayes assumes that the presence of each word in a movie review is independent of the presence of other words, given the sentiment label (positive or negative). For example, knowing that a review contains the word "great" does not influence the likelihood of it containing the word "horrible", and vice versa. Although this assumption is very simplistic and may not hold true in practice, Naive Bayes often performs well in text classification tasks.

Conditional Probability: Naive Bayes calculates the conditional probability of each word given the sentiment label. For instance, it estimates the probability of seeing the word "great" in a positive review and the probability of seeing the word "horrible" in a negative review independently.The classifier combines the probabilities of individual words to calculate the overall probability of each sentiment label given the input review. It does so by multiplying the conditional probabilities of each word given the sentiment label.

Interpretability/ Feature Importance: Naive Bayes implicitly ranks features (words) based on their contribution to the classification decision. Words with higher conditional probabilities for a particular class are considered more important for predicting that class. This allows users to identify which words are most influential in determining the predicted class.

NB Feature importance:¶

In [26]:
# Identify the most important features
feature_probabilities_nb = np.exp(classifier_nb.feature_log_prob_)

Note: .feature_probabilities are the posterior probabilities that a word will appear in a document of a given class, $p(w|k)$. But we want the posterior probability that a document is of a given class, given it contains that word, $p(k|w)$

This cab be obtained by Bayes Theorem:

$p(\text{pos} | w) = \frac{p(w | \text{pos})}{p(w | \text{pos}) + p(w | \text{neg})}$

In this equation:

  • $p(\text{pos} | w)$ represents the posterior probability that a document is positive given it contains the word $w$. This probability indicates how likely it is for a document to be classified as positive when the word

$w$ is present giving us a quantitative measure of how important a token is for classifying documents into different classes.

  • $p(w | \text{pos})$ is the posterior probability that the word ( w ) will appear in a positive document.
  • $p(w | \text{neg})$ is the posterior probability that the word ( w ) will appear in a negative document.

This equation allows us to calculate the probability of a document belonging to a certain class (e.g., positive) given that it contains a specific word ( w ).

In [27]:
# calculate (denominator in equation above):
total_word_likelihood = np.sum(feature_probabilities_nb, axis=0)
# Calculate the probability of each word being associated with the negative class (p(w|neg))
prob_negative_given_word = feature_probabilities_nb[0,:]/total_word_likelihood
# Calculate the probability of each word being associated with the positive class (p(w|pos))
prob_positive_given_word = feature_probabilities_nb[1,:]/total_word_likelihood

Support Vector Machine¶

Unlike Naive Bayes, which is a probabilistic classifier, SVM is a discriminative classifier that finds the optimal hyperplane to separate different classes in the feature space. This problem can be formulated as a constrained optimization problem, where we seek to maximize the margin between the support vectors while minimizing the classification error.

Support vectors: In our context, these are the movie reviews that lie closest to the decision boundary, i.e., the hyperplane that delineates positive and negative reviews. These support vectors are crucial because they define the position and orientation of the decision boundary. They represent the most informative and influential reviews in terms of distinguishing between positive and negative sentiments.

The SVM algorithm constructs the decision boundary such that it maximizes the margin, or the distance between the hyperplane and the closest support vectors from each class. By doing so, the algorithm aims to achieve the best possible separation between positive and negative reviews.

Interpretability: SVMs make use of kernels and Linear kernels result in linear decision boundaries, which are easier to interpret and understand. The decision boundary is a hyperplane in the feature space, and the coefficients associated with each feature indicate the importance of that feature in determining the classification decision. This interpretability can be valuable for understanding which features are most relevant for sentiment analysis in movie reviews.

Some math:¶

The decision function is: $f(x) = \mathbf{w} \cdot \mathbf{x} + b$

  • If f(x) is positive, the SVM predicts the positive class.
  • If f(x) is negative, the SVM predicts the negative class.

The weight vector $(\mathbf{w})$ in the above equation is directly related to the coefficients returned by .coef_ attribute

Interpretation:

$(\mathbf{w})$ act as weights that determine the importance of each feature in the decision-making process. In the above case, each token is a feature and we are weighting the impotance of each token.

Analogy with Linear Regression: In linear regression, the coefficients that multiply the input features are often referred to as weights. These weights determine the contribution of each feature to the predicted output. Similarly, in SVMs, $(\mathbf{w})$ determines the orientation of the decision boundary in the feature space, and its components (or the individual elements or values that make up the vector) can be seen as weights assigned to each feature.

Also note that:

$\mathbf{w}$ can be expressed as: $\mathbf{w} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} \alpha_i y_i \mathbf{x_i} $

Here, $\alpha_i$ represents the Lagrange multiplier associated with the $i$-th support vector, $y_i$ is the corresponding class label, and $\mathbf{x_i}$ is the $i$-th support vector. The coefficients returned by .coef_ are directly related to the Lagrange multipliers ($\alpha_i$) used in the optimization problem, as they are used to compute the weight vector $\mathbf{w}$.

classifier_svm.dual_coef_ corresponds to the $\alpha_i y_i$ according to the documentation.

X_train_binary[classifier_svm.support_] corresponds to $x_i$. It returns the subset of the training data X_train consisting of only the support vectors identified by the SVM modele. We will find the dot protuct of these two to get the weights associated with each feautre.

We can find the dot product between these two values to get the weights. These weights should equal the weights returned by .coef_.

Grid Search to find C:¶

In the above code we set $C=.1$ but but this parameter was chose after 'tuning'. I show how to do this below.

$C$ is a hyperparameter that controls the trade-off between maximizing the margin and minimizing the classification error. It represents the penalty imposed on misclassifications during the training process.

When the value of $C$ is small, the SVM algorithm prioritizes maximizing the margin, even if it results in misclassifying some training examples. This approach tends to produce simpler decision boundaries with larger margins, which may generalize better to unseen data. However, too small a value of $C$ can lead to underfitting, where the model may fail to capture the complexities of the data.

On the other hand, when the value of $C$ is large, the algorithm places more emphasis on correctly classifying all training examples, potentially leading to smaller margins and more complex decision boundaries. While this approach may result in better performance on the training data, it also increases the risk of overfitting, where the model memorizes the training data instead of learning general patterns.

Random Forests¶

Random Forest is an ensemble learning algorithm and operates by constructing multiple decision trees during training and outputs the mode (most frequent) class label among the individual trees for classification.

Bagging: During the training phase, Random Forest builds a collection of decision trees. Each decision tree is constructed using a random subset of the training data and a random subset of the features, which are typically words in the case of text classification. At each node of the decision tree, a random subset of features is considered for splitting, and the best split is chosen based on criteria such as Gini impurity or information gain. This process continues recursively until a stopping criterion is met, such as reaching a maximum tree depth or a minimum number of samples in a leaf node.

Majority Voting: Once all decision trees are built, predictions are made independently by each tree. For a given input text document, each decision tree predicts a class label based on the majority class of the training samples in the corresponding leaf node. The final predicted class label for the input document is determined by aggregating the individual predictions from all decision trees. This can be done by taking a majority vote (mode) among the predictions.

Document term matrix:¶

Random forests is a very computationally intensive algorithm, so we will cut the number of features way way down just so this can run in a reasonable amount of time.

Feature Importance:¶

MDI importances:¶

feature_importances_ gives a numerical importance score assigned to each feature by the Random Forest classifier and is calculated using the Mean Decrease in Impurity (MDI) method. This method computes the importance score of a feature based on the decrease in impurity (typically measured using the Gini impurity) achieved by splitting the data based on that feature during the construction of individual decision trees in the Random Forest ensemble.

But feature importances simply tells us which one of the features were more useful when building the model. They should not to be interpreted as coefficients (we can not interpret them as "correlations" or "strength coefficients") giving a direct dependence between predictor and target. If your model does not generalize to validation data, then feature importances have no meaning 1.

Feature importances are specific to the training data used to build the model. If the model does not generalize well to unseen data, such as validation or test data, then the feature importances may not accurately reflect the true importance of features in making predictions on new data.

Permutation importances (docs)¶

Another approach is to calculate the permutation importances of rf that are computed on a held out test set. They measure the decrease in model performance (for eample, in terms of accuracy/F1 etc., in classification tasks) when the values of a feature are randomly permuted. By comparing the model's performance with the original feature values to its performance with permuted feature values, we can determine the importance of each feature in making accurate predictions.

The permutation importances are computed on a metric of your choice(accuracy/precision/recall etc.), they are easier to interpret and can in some sense be seen as a "strength coefficient", since they answer the question: "How much does the performance of my model degrade if I shuffle this predictor?"1

In [43]:

# Measures the decrease in model performance when the values of each feature are randomly shuffled. 
# The analysis is repeated 10 to obtain estimates of feature importance. 
# The results include the mean importance, standard deviation, and confidence interval for each feature.
permute_importances = permutation_importance(
    classifier_rf, rf_X_test.toarray(), y_test, n_repeats=100, random_state=42, n_jobs=5, scoring="accuracy"
)

ROC¶

The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve is a graphical representation of the performance of a binary classification model across different threshold settings. It plots the true positive rate (Sensitivity) against the false positive rate (1 - Specificity) for various threshold values. Each point on the curve represents the performance of the model at a particular threshold setting. A diagonal line from the bottom left corner to the top right corner represents the performance of a random classifier. The ROC curve looks in more depth at the underlying scores / probability statements that indicate how sure the classifier is.

A perfect classifier would have a ROC curve that passes through the top left corner (true positive rate of 1 and false positive rate of 0), indicating that it achieves perfect sensitivity (correctly identifies all positive samples) while making no false positive predictions.

The area under the ROC curve (AUC) is a summary measure of the classifier's performance, with higher values indicating better discrimination between the positive and negative classes. It provides a single value summarizing the overall performance of the classifier.

In [75]:
